Lucr. iii. 848; Livy, iii. 8. “ While the mind wavers in uncertainty, the smallest trifie turns it either way.’' Madame Dacier, Westerhovius‚ Ruhnken, and others, consider this a metaphor from a pair of scales in equilibrium. That which turns a scale is properly called momentum, from moveo. Donatus refers it to a huge weighty mass, which, while it is still in its erect posi- tion, and hanging in suspense, is overturned by the slightest touch. In the beautiful story of Myrrha, Ovid, Met. x. 378, there is a passage which the commentators suppose to be in imitation of this :
